How many positive two-digit integers have an odd number of positive factors?
inference:
A positive two-digit integer has an odd number of positive factors if and only if it is a perfect square.
The perfect squares between 10 and 99 are 16, 25, 36, 49, 64, and 81.
So there are $\boxed{6}$ such two-digit integers.
Final Answer: $\boxed{6}$. I hope it is correct.
ground_truth: Only square numbers have an odd number of factors. The $\boxed{6}$ two-digit squares are 16, 25, 36, 49, 64 and 81.
